{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1783895659,"nonce":"4aVjMOGUshVVXJ1OQuuftaUlenM=","message":"Fixed in PR #102 (squash 34510dd).\n\nChose option 1 (store both names): added `ProjectionItem.internal_alias`, the\nprojection's own `AS` that a column list suppresses, re-emitted under the column\nlist so a body clause referencing it resolves. Threaded through the reverse\nparser, MySQL introspection (`apply_view_column_names`), KDL ser/de, the\nrenderer, and all backends.\n\nThe reverse parser's clause resolution is now:\n- dialect-specific: PostgreSQL protects an output alias only as a standalone\n  ORDER BY/GROUP BY item (never nested, never in HAVING); MySQL/SQLite protect at\n  any depth;\n- scope-aware: single- vs multi-source (a same-name `a.id AS id` is a source\n  column single-source, but disambiguates a joined column multi-source); a\n  renamed plain column (`q.amount AS renamed`) is protected, a self-naming one is\n  not;\n- pruned: an inner alias no clause references is dropped.\n\nVerified: renders valid SQL on live PostgreSQL/MySQL/SQLite (was invalid);\nround-trips through the corpus (5 new alias cases), SQLite verbatim\nintrospection, and KDL. Full suite + live PG/MySQL green. Local codex clean;\nGitHub Codex bot's one comment was on a pre-fix commit and is addressed.\n\nKnown residual, split to a new bug: the reverse parser has no source-column\ncatalog, so a source column colliding with a projection alias — or a backend\nexpanding a clause alias to its expression on deparse (PostgreSQL, MySQL) — makes\nsuch a view re-plan a harmless CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW each run (always valid SQL,\nmeaning preserved; the same idempotent gap the body-unknown view path accepts).\nDocumented on `ProjectionItem::internal_alias`. Follow-up: catalog-based view\nname resolution.","files":null}]}